<!doctype linuxdoc system>
<article>

<title> Information for DEC 21030 Users (aka TGA)
<author> The XFree86 Project, Inc.
<date> 21 September 1996
<toc>

<p>
<sect>DEC 21030
<p>
<itemize>
<item>The DEC 21030 is now supported by XFree86 in this first release of
XFree86 3.2. This server is still experimental but seems to work well.

<item>Current Known Problems

<enum>
<item>VT switching isn't elegant enough. Once the Xserver has started
you can switch to another VT using the standard key sequence, but when
switching back to the Xserver's VT the screen is not restored. Executing
`xrefresh' from your window manager or xterm should clear this up.

<item>If you have PEX fonts installed, the Xserver will coredump. Only
workaround for the moment is to delete the PEX font files.

<item>Only one modeline is accepted, this will be the first viable one
that matches other criteria.

<item>Due to 3. Virtual Resolutions is not supported either.

<item>VideoRam is currently limited to 2MB and is not changeable.

<item>The 8plane 21030 is currently the only supported chipset. I don't
have access to the 24plane or the 24plane3D chip.
</enum>

<item>The following options may be specified for the 21030 driver:
<descrip>
<tag>Option &dquot;dac_8_bit&dquot;</tag>
	Turn on 8Bit BT485 RamDac.
<tag>Option &dquot;dac_6_bit&dquot;</tag>
	Turn on 6Bit BT485 RamDac.
<tag>MemBase &dquot;0x???????&dquot;</tag>
	This setting has to be used, Check /proc/pci for the 21030 and
	look for the "Prefetchable 32 bit memory at 0x???????" and enter
	this as your MemBase setting.
<tag>Option &dquot;hw_cursor&dquot;</tag>
	Not yet available, but will turn on 21030's hardware cursor.
<tag>Option &dquot;bt485_curs&dquot;</tag>
	Not yet available, but will turn on the BT485 RamDac's cursor.

</descrip>
<item>No acceleration features of the 21030 have been taken advantage of yet!
</itemize>

<sect> Additional Notes <p>
The code for the 21030 as yet - has only been tested on DEC's UDB box, better
known as the Multia in other environments, in a Linux environment.

<sect> Known modelines <p>
Use these ModeLines as a starting point and tune them, although you can
use xvidtune to adjust these parameters, it may not be as flexible as
manually editing them for the best display.

ENSURE YOUR MONITOR IS CAPABLE OF THESE RESOLUTIONS BEFORE USING !!!!!!!

<verb>
ModeLine "1280x1024@72hz" 130    1280 1312 1472 1696 1024 1027 1030 1063
ModeLine "1280x1024@66hz" 120    1280 1312 1472 1696 1024 1027 1030 1063
ModeLine "1280x1024@60hz" 108    1280 1324 1508 1708 1024 1027 1030 1056
ModeLine "1152x900@72hz"  104    1152 1216 1328 1504 900  906  916  960
ModeLine "1152x900@66hz"  92.98  1152 1172 1304 1504 900  902  906  937
ModeLine "1024x768@70hz"  75     1024 1048 1184 1328 768  771  777  806
ModeLine "1024x768@72hz"  74.37  1024 1040 1168 1296 768  769  775  797
ModeLine "1024x768@60hz"  65     1024 1080 1144 1344 768  775  784  810
ModeLine "800x600"        50     800  856  976  1040 600  601  607  636
ModeLine "800x600"        40     800  840  968  1056 600  601  605  628
ModeLine "640x480"        31     640  664  704  832  480  489  492  520
ModeLine "640x480"        25.175 640  664  688  700  480  490  492  525
</verb>

<p>
<verb>
$XFree86$
</verb>

</article>
